passages.text: 2Q earnings beat but reiterate Neutral on full valuation
DG 12m Price Target: \$126.00 Price: \$111.71 Upside: 12.8%

DG closed up \(0.5\%\) (vs. S&P \(+0.3\%\) ) after its 2Q top- line and EPS beat, along with raising FY25 guidance. Key takeaways include: 1) the company posted a slight comp beat from broad based growth across categories; 2) the gross margin improvement was largely driven by shrink improvements; and 3) guidance was raised based on the 2Q beat and improved 2H outlook.

DG's management team has worked hard to improve the company's positioning through its Back to Basics program, which has resulted in better comp trends and improved margins. While we think the company still has room for margin improvement over the long term, we think the stock is now pricing in its better fundamentals. We reiterate our Neutral rating with a new 12- month price target of \$126.

categories: SSS of \(+2.8\%\) came in slightly above GS/Refinitiv consensus at \(+2.5\%\) , driven by increased ticket of \(+1.2\%\) (down from \(+2.7\%\) in Q1), and traffic of \(+1.5\%\) (up from \(- 0.3\%\) in Q1). Basket growth was driven by an increase in both AUR and average items per basket. The company also called out that this was the second consecutive quarter they have seen growth across all categories (consumables, seasonal, home products, and apparel). Additionally, management noted that they grew share in both consumables and non- consumables during the quarter. From a cadence perspective comps were \(+2\%\) in May, June, and July with comps June and July being the strongest. The company attributes the strong comp performance to improved execution and their value and convenience proposition resonating with customers across all income cohorts. Their core

customer increased spending while they continued to see trade- in from middle and upper- income customers. We believe this trade- in could be partially attributed to other retailer bankruptcies. Management reaffirmed their long- term comp guidance of \(2.0 - 3.0\%\) , and noted that they feel comfortable in that range moving forward.

Gross margin increase largely driven by shrink improvements: The company's gross margin on \(0.1\%\) was above our estimate of \(30.5\%\) and consensus estimate of \(30.6\%\) . This is the highest gross margin result since 1Q23. The y/y increase of 137 bps was primarily due to lower shrink \((+108\) bps) and higher inventory markups, and lower damages partially offset by an increased LIFO provision, increased markdowns, and increased distribution costs. In the 2H, the company continues to expect shrink to be a tailwind with y/y improvements in both quarters, but to a lesser extent in Q4 due to a tougher compare. The company is also seeing improvements in damages with an out- performance in the quarter though they are keeping their goal for damages for the year of flat to slightly favorable the same. The company continues to expect their initiatives around DG Media, delivery, and non- consumables to be mid and longer- term margin driver of gross margin.

Guidance raised off of 2Q beat and improved 2H outlook: The company raised FY25 guidance, including higher net sales growth of \(+4.3 - 4.8\%\) , compared to \(+3.7 - 4.7\%\) prior (vs. GS/consensus of \(4.5\% /4.5\%\) ) and SSS of \(+2.1 - 2.6\%\) , compared to \(+1.5 - 2.5\%\) prior (vs. GS/consensus of \(+2.4\% / + 2.3\%\) ). Additionally, DG raised its EPS guidance range by \(- 10\%\) at the midpoint to \(\) 5.80- 6.30\(compared to\) \ \(5.20 - 5.80\) prior (vs. GS/consensus of \(\) 5.76/\(\) 5.74\$ ). Management noted that their raised guidance is largely to reflect their out- performance during the quarter and improved outlook on the 2H of the year, while considering the uncertainty around the consumer. The low end of the guidance range incorporates increased pressure on spending in 2H.

Following DG's 2Q out performance, we are increasing our FY25 EPS estimate by \(+5.4\%\) to \(\) 6.07\(from\) \ \(5.76\) to primarily reflect today's beat. Additionally, our FY26 EPS estimates increase by \(+3.1\%\) to \(\) 6.59\(from\) \ \(6.39\) on the higher FY25 base. We decrease our FY27 EPS estimate slightly by \(0.9\%\) to \(\) 7.05\(from\) \ \(7.12\) .

We are Neutral rated on DG. Our 12- month price target increases to \(\) 126\(from\) \ \(116\) prior), based on our higher estimates and market multiple \((23.2x\) vs 21.4x prior), partially offset by lower downside/base/upside relative P/E multiples of \(70\% /80\% /85\%\) (vs. \(70\% /80\% /90\%\) prior) due to an intense competitive environment keeping comp upside limited.

Downside risks include a de minimis e- commerce offering; mix pressure on margins from consumables; slower ramp of initiatives; competitive pressures; greater inflationary costs regarding freight and/or wages.

Upside risk include new store growth driving top- line improvements; comp lift from store remodels; margin expansion from DC and supply chain investments and discipline cost management; continued e- commerce expansion driving new incremental revenue and customer reach; shopper mix shift towards higher margin products and affluent customer trade- in.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
